<subSubSection id="C309F2B5FFB6A654BA3AFD4BFBB47C72" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BACA13EFFB6A654BA3AFD4BFAF17AD2" blockId="2.[833,1472,685,997]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="B9677D2CFFB6A654BA3AFD4BFC7E7BF2" bold="true" box="[833,966,685,709]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="B9677D2CFFB6A654BA3AFD4BFC0C7BF2" bold="true" box="[833,948,685,709]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
–
</emphasis>
New species of small size compared to the other species of the genus, with a total length of 15.8 mm. Carapace with the anterior margin straight, almost acarinate and weakly granulated to smooth; furrows shallow. Metasomal carinae moderately marked; ventral carinae vestigial on segments I and II, weakly marked on segment III. Dentate margins of fixed and movable fingers of pedipalp chela with 6 rows of granules, not well delimited. Pectinal tooth count 4- 
<quantity id="4CEB0CDBFFB6A654BCEFFC68FA787A92" box="[1428,1472,910,933]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
female. Genital operculum plates have a sub-oval shape. Trichobothriotaxy of 
<typeStatus id="54A81F9CFFB6A654BD52FC28FBD87AD2" box="[1065,1120,974,997]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Type</typeStatus>
B, orthobothriotaxic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BACA13EFFB6A654BA3AFBEBFBB47C72" blockId="2.[833,1472,1037,1349]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="B9677D2CFFB6A654BA3AFBEBFC557D12" bold="true" box="[833,1005,1037,1061]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="B9677D2CFFB6A654BA3AFBEBFC637D12" bold="true" box="[833,987,1037,1061]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Relationships.</emphasis>
–
</emphasis>
By its general morphology and the pattern of pigmentation, 
<taxonomicName id="4C13DABDFFB6A654BAA1FBC8FBC97D72" authority="Lourenço &amp; Sun &amp; Zhu, 2010" authorityName="Lourenço &amp; Sun &amp; Zhu" authorityYear="2010" box="[986,1137,1070,1093]" class="Arachnida" family="Chaerilidae" genus="Chaerilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thai" status="new species">
<emphasis id="B9677D2CFFB6A654BAA1FBC8FBC97D72" box="[986,1137,1070,1093]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Chaerilus thai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A254C057FFB6A654BD05FBC8FAB87D72" box="[1150,1280,1070,1093]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, can be associated with 
<taxonomicName id="4C13DABDFFB6A654BA07FBA8FB407D52" authority="Pocock. The" authorityName="Pocock. The" authorityYear="2010" box="[892,1272,1102,1125]" class="Arachnida" family="Chaerilidae" genus="Chaerilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="celebensis" status="new species">
<emphasis id="B9677D2CFFB6A654BA07FBA8FBDA7D52" box="[892,1122,1102,1125]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Chaerilus celebensis</emphasis>
Pocock. The
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A254C057FFB6A654BC79FBA8FA317D52" box="[1282,1417,1102,1125]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
can, however, be distinguished by the following features: (i) a smaller total size and distinct morphometric values (see Table 1), (ii) a carapace very weakly granulated to smooth, (iii) an overall darker pigmentation than that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C13DABDFFB6A654BC53FB28FA007DD2" authorityName="Pocock. The" authorityYear="2010" box="[1320,1464,1230,1253]" class="Arachnida" family="Chaerilidae" genus="Chaerilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="celebensis">
<emphasis id="B9677D2CFFB6A654BC53FB28FA007DD2" box="[1320,1464,1230,1253]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">C. celebensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; are particularly marked the dorsal surface of metasomal segments I to IV, pedipalps, chelicerae and ventral aspect, including pectines.
</paragraph>
